  	<table width="640">
      <tr>
        <td>&nbsp;</td>
        <td>&nbsp;</td>
      </tr>
      <tr valign="top">
        <td height="870" colspan="2"><blockquote>
          <p align="left"><span class="style3">No where is your positive attitude more appreciated by others than when you are at work. Some reasons for this are:</span></p>
        </blockquote>
          <ul>
            <li class="style3">
              <div align="left">For many of your co-workers, work is not what they would prefer to be doing. Working with a positive person makes their day more enjoyable.</div>
            </li>
            <li class="style3">
              <div align="left">Some co-workers have extremely difficult private lives. Where they work can be a place to find positive people who can help them forget some of their difficulties.</div>
            </li>
            <li class="style3">
              <div align="left">Supervisors depend upon the positive attitudes of employees to establish a team spirit. Positive attitudes among a few employees makes everyone's job easier.</div>
            </li>
            <li>
              <div align="left"><span class="style3">Approximately half of a working person's waking hours are spent in the workplace, probably more for you since you are in a management position. Without some positive attitudes around, this amount of time could seem to drag on and on. </span></div>
            </li>
          </ul>
          <p align="left" class="style3">Both positive and negative attitudes are contagious. A bad attitude spreads like wildfire through the workplace. As a supervisor you can put that fire out as fast as it started. Good attitudes can spread like warm butter on an ear of corn. It starts at one end and flows to each and every kernel until the whole cob is covered. Don't underestimate the impact you have on your crew. If you show up and are not smiling and acknowledging each and every member of the staff the rumors start. &quot;Watch out, you want to stay away from ____ today, are they in a mood!&quot; Everyone realizes we have a life outside of work, but we need to leave our problems outside the workplace. This can be difficult and if you feel it is not possible you will need to talk with your supervisor. </p>
        <p align="left" class="style3">Your guests can tell when they walk into the restaurant when the work environment is comfortable, efficient and friendly by noticing the attitudes of workers. There is more laughter and smiles. Employees are more tolerant of each other. There is just that &quot;Feeling&quot; in the air. Work is viewed more as a challenge than as a series of tasks or interuptions. Negative attitudes can turn all this sour and chase those customers away before you even have the chance to serve them.</p>        </td>
      </tr>
    </table>
    <table width="640">
      <tr>
        <td width="114"><span class="style3 style7"><img src="../../../images/man_thinking.gif" width="68" height="118"></span></td>
        <td width="514" valign="middle"><div align="center"><span class="style3 style7">THOUGHTS TO PONDER</span></div></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td colspan="2"><ul class="style7">
          <li class="style3">
            <div align="left">You may not hear it expressed verbally (it is difficult to compliment another on such a sensitve characteristic), but your positive attitude is deeply appreciated by your co-workers.</div>
          </li>
          <li class="style3">
            <div align="left">You either contribute or subtract from a better work environment through your attitude. There is no way to remain neutral.</div>
          </li>
          <li class="style3">
            <div align="left">You contribute to productivity through your many skills and competencies; you also contribute more than you suspect through your positive attitude. </div>
          </li>
          </ul>
        <p>&nbsp;</p></td>
      </tr>
